</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Breast cancer is a heterogeneous disease, which comprises several molecular and genetic subtypes, each with characteristic clinicobiologic behavior and imaging patterns. Traditional classification of breast cancer is based on the histopathologic features but offers limited prognostic value. Novel molecular characterization of breast cancer with cellular markers has allowed a new classification that offers prognostic value, with predictive categories of disease aggressiveness. These molecular signatures also open the door to personalized therapeutic options, with new receptor-targeted therapies. For example, invasive cancer subtypes such as the luminal A and B subtypes show better prognosis and response to hormone receptor–targeted therapies compared with the triple-negative subtypes; on the other hand, triple-negative tumors respond better than luminal tumors to chemotherapy. Tumors that display amplification of the oncogene <i>ERBB2</i> (also known as the HER2/neu oncogene) respond to drugs directed against this oncogene, such as trastuzumab. The imaging aspects of tumors correlate with molecular subgroups, as well as other pathologic features such as nuclear grade. Smooth tumor margins at mammography may be suggestive of a triple-negative breast cancer, and a human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)–positive tumor is characteristically a spiculated mass with calcifications. Low-grade ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is better detected with mammography, although magnetic resonance (MR) imaging may allow better characterization of high-grade DCIS. MR imaging diffusion sequences show higher values for the apparent diffusion coefficient for triple-negative and HER2-positive subtypes, compared with luminal A and B tumors. MR imaging is also a useful tool in the prediction of tumor response after chemotherapy, especially for triple-negative and HER2-positive subtypes.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130049">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130049">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig1.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; hematoxylin-phloxine-saffron stain) of normal breast tissue shows the two epithelial cell types of the normal duct and lobular system of the breast. Luminal cells line the ducts, and myoepithelial cells abut the basement membrane. From these two types of cells originate the various molecular subgroups of breast cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig2a.jpeg" height="1189" width="599" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral-oblique mammographic image of the superior portion of the left breast shows a round mass with ill-defined margins, without associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Doppler US image shows a round hypoechoic mass with fairly well-circumscribed contours and a thick hyperechoic halo, mild posterior enhancement, and some peripheral vascularity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.106 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) obtained after contrast material administration shows a round mass with irregular margins and rim enhancement. <b>(d)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows hyperintensity of the mass. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (6.289/3.106) obtained at the level of the axilla shows an abnormally enlarged lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig2b.jpeg" height="574" width="722" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral-oblique mammographic image of the superior portion of the left breast shows a round mass with ill-defined margins, without associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Doppler US image shows a round hypoechoic mass with fairly well-circumscribed contours and a thick hyperechoic halo, mild posterior enhancement, and some peripheral vascularity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.106 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) obtained after contrast material administration shows a round mass with irregular margins and rim enhancement. <b>(d)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows hyperintensity of the mass. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (6.289/3.106) obtained at the level of the axilla shows an abnormally enlarged lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig2c.jpeg" height="574" width="752" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral-oblique mammographic image of the superior portion of the left breast shows a round mass with ill-defined margins, without associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Doppler US image shows a round hypoechoic mass with fairly well-circumscribed contours and a thick hyperechoic halo, mild posterior enhancement, and some peripheral vascularity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.106 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) obtained after contrast material administration shows a round mass with irregular margins and rim enhancement. <b>(d)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows hyperintensity of the mass. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (6.289/3.106) obtained at the level of the axilla shows an abnormally enlarged lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig2d.jpeg" height="535" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral-oblique mammographic image of the superior portion of the left breast shows a round mass with ill-defined margins, without associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Doppler US image shows a round hypoechoic mass with fairly well-circumscribed contours and a thick hyperechoic halo, mild posterior enhancement, and some peripheral vascularity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.106 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) obtained after contrast material administration shows a round mass with irregular margins and rim enhancement. <b>(d)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows hyperintensity of the mass. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (6.289/3.106) obtained at the level of the axilla shows an abnormally enlarged lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig2e.jpeg" height="535" width="689" aria-labelledby="fig2e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2e</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral-oblique mammographic image of the superior portion of the left breast shows a round mass with ill-defined margins, without associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Doppler US image shows a round hypoechoic mass with fairly well-circumscribed contours and a thick hyperechoic halo, mild posterior enhancement, and some peripheral vascularity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.106 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) obtained after contrast material administration shows a round mass with irregular margins and rim enhancement. <b>(d)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows hyperintensity of the mass. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (6.289/3.106) obtained at the level of the axilla shows an abnormally enlarged lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig2e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig3a.jpeg" height="814" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 62-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass with a complex echo pattern and posterior enhancement. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/288.9) shows an oval mass with heterogeneous T2 signal intensity, with hyperintense foci. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.284/3.1) show an oval microlobulated mass with fairly smooth margins, heterogeneous enhancement, and rapid washout. Note the markedly enlarged axillary lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig3b.jpeg" height="766" width="566" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 62-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass with a complex echo pattern and posterior enhancement. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/288.9) shows an oval mass with heterogeneous T2 signal intensity, with hyperintense foci. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.284/3.1) show an oval microlobulated mass with fairly smooth margins, heterogeneous enhancement, and rapid washout. Note the markedly enlarged axillary lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig3c.jpeg" height="766" width="621" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 62-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass with a complex echo pattern and posterior enhancement. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/288.9) shows an oval mass with heterogeneous T2 signal intensity, with hyperintense foci. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.284/3.1) show an oval microlobulated mass with fairly smooth margins, heterogeneous enhancement, and rapid washout. Note the markedly enlarged axillary lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig3d.jpeg" height="766" width="667" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 62-year-old woman who presented with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a lobulated hypoechoic mass with a complex echo pattern and posterior enhancement. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/288.9) shows an oval mass with heterogeneous T2 signal intensity, with hyperintense foci. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.284/3.1) show an oval microlobulated mass with fairly smooth margins, heterogeneous enhancement, and rapid washout. Note the markedly enlarged axillary lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig4a.jpeg" height="668" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnified mammographic view shows suspicious linear and branching microcalcifications. <b>(b, c)</b> Early axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.104) obtained at two contiguous levels show multifocal involvement, with two small enhancing spiculated masses. <b>(d)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection shows the spiculated enhancing masses and associated segmental nonmass enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig4b.jpeg" height="668" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnified mammographic view shows suspicious linear and branching microcalcifications. <b>(b, c)</b> Early axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.104) obtained at two contiguous levels show multifocal involvement, with two small enhancing spiculated masses. <b>(d)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection shows the spiculated enhancing masses and associated segmental nonmass enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig4c.jpeg" height="691" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnified mammographic view shows suspicious linear and branching microcalcifications. <b>(b, c)</b> Early axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.104) obtained at two contiguous levels show multifocal involvement, with two small enhancing spiculated masses. <b>(d)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection shows the spiculated enhancing masses and associated segmental nonmass enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig4d.jpeg" height="691" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnified mammographic view shows suspicious linear and branching microcalcifications. <b>(b, c)</b> Early axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.104) obtained at two contiguous levels show multifocal involvement, with two small enhancing spiculated masses. <b>(d)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection shows the spiculated enhancing masses and associated segmental nonmass enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig5a.jpeg" height="934" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Intermediate-grade ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman who presented with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal computed tomographic image obtained after the initial imaging evaluation with lumbar radiography (not shown) confirms widespread lytic bone lesions that were strongly suggestive of metastatic involvement. <b>(b)</b> Magnified craniocaudal mammographic view of the right breast shows a small spiculated mass with associated pleomorphic microcalcifications. <b>(c)</b> US image obtained during core-needle biopsy shows an irregular mass with indistinct margins and a hypoechoic echo pattern, as well as posterior shadowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig5b.jpeg" height="599" width="881" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Intermediate-grade ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman who presented with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal computed tomographic image obtained after the initial imaging evaluation with lumbar radiography (not shown) confirms widespread lytic bone lesions that were strongly suggestive of metastatic involvement. <b>(b)</b> Magnified craniocaudal mammographic view of the right breast shows a small spiculated mass with associated pleomorphic microcalcifications. <b>(c)</b> US image obtained during core-needle biopsy shows an irregular mass with indistinct margins and a hypoechoic echo pattern, as well as posterior shadowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig5c.jpeg" height="600" width="893" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Intermediate-grade ER-negative PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman who presented with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal computed tomographic image obtained after the initial imaging evaluation with lumbar radiography (not shown) confirms widespread lytic bone lesions that were strongly suggestive of metastatic involvement. <b>(b)</b> Magnified craniocaudal mammographic view of the right breast shows a small spiculated mass with associated pleomorphic microcalcifications. <b>(c)</b> US image obtained during core-needle biopsy shows an irregular mass with indistinct margins and a hypoechoic echo pattern, as well as posterior shadowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6a.jpeg" height="612" width="716" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6b.jpeg" height="612" width="759" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6c.jpeg" height="622" width="749" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6d.jpeg" height="622" width="726" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6e.jpeg" height="636" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig6e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6e</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6f.jpeg" height="636" width="725" aria-labelledby="fig6f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6f</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig6g.jpeg" height="627" width="749" aria-labelledby="fig6g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6g</span> High-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal mammographic view shows three spiculated masses involving the inner and outer portions of the right breast, with extensive associated microcalcifications. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image (2000/270) shows a hypointense spiculated mass. <b>(c, d)</b> Early <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (6.289/3.105) show a strongly and heterogeneously enhancing spiculated mass with rapid washout. <b>(e)</b> Reconstructed maximum intensity projection image (63.9/10,530) obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection depicts multicentric disease with spiculated masses. <b>(f)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a mixed hypo- and hyperintense spiculated mass. <b>(g)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> allows precise tumor delineation, with hypointensity in the tumor, a finding that indicates diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig6g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig7a.jpeg" height="715" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig2a">Fig 2</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (10,530/63.9) (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a hyperintense round mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> depicts hyperintensity within the tumor, a finding suggestive of intratumoral necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig7b.jpeg" height="715" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with axillary metastasis in a 53-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig2a">Fig 2</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (10,530/63.9) (<i>b</i> value = 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows a hyperintense round mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial ADC map (section thickness, 3 mm) reconstructed from images obtained at <i>b</i> values of 50 and 750 sec/mm<sup>2</sup> depicts hyperintensity within the tumor, a finding suggestive of intratumoral necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig8.jpeg" height="881" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Triple-negative high-grade infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an axillary metastasis in a 62-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig3a">Fig 3</a>) after neoadjuvant chemotherapy. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.284/3.101) obtained after treatment shows a partial response to treatment, with a decrease in size of both the intramammary tumor and the axillary metastasis, compared with the pretreatment images (see <a href="#fig3d">Fig 3d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig9a.jpeg" height="912" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Multicentric high-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman before and after neoadjuvant chemotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Fig 6</a>). <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.105) obtained at the time of diagnosis shows an enhancing mass. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment axial T1-weighted MR image (7.996/4.603) obtained before contrast material injection shows a decrease in size of the spiculated mass. <b>(c)</b> Posttreatment axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.288/3.105) shows minimal residual enhancement in the spiculated mass. The findings at surgical pathologic examination disclosed a partial response to neoadjuvant chemotherapy, with discontinuous residual disease (the largest residual tumor measured 2 cm).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig9b.jpeg" height="785" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Multicentric high-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman before and after neoadjuvant chemotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Fig 6</a>). <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.105) obtained at the time of diagnosis shows an enhancing mass. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment axial T1-weighted MR image (7.996/4.603) obtained before contrast material injection shows a decrease in size of the spiculated mass. <b>(c)</b> Posttreatment axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.288/3.105) shows minimal residual enhancement in the spiculated mass. The findings at surgical pathologic examination disclosed a partial response to neoadjuvant chemotherapy, with discontinuous residual disease (the largest residual tumor measured 2 cm).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig9c.jpeg" height="785" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Multicentric high-grade ER-positive HER2-negative (luminal A or B subtype) infiltrating ductal carcinoma with an extensive intraductal component in a 30-year-old woman before and after neoadjuvant chemotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Fig 6</a>). <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.289/3.105) obtained at the time of diagnosis shows an enhancing mass. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment axial T1-weighted MR image (7.996/4.603) obtained before contrast material injection shows a decrease in size of the spiculated mass. <b>(c)</b> Posttreatment axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image (6.288/3.105) shows minimal residual enhancement in the spiculated mass. The findings at surgical pathologic examination disclosed a partial response to neoadjuvant chemotherapy, with discontinuous residual disease (the largest residual tumor measured 2 cm).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig10a.jpeg" height="653" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> ER-positive PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 43-year-old woman treated with neoadjuvant chemotherapy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR images (10/4.2) obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> contrast material injection show an enhancing irregular spiculated mass in <b>b</b>; the signal void corresponds to the metallic postbiopsy marker. <b>(c, d)</b> After the completion of neoadjuvant chemotherapy, axial T1-weighted MR images obtained before (8.159/4.603) <b>(c)</b> and after (6.289/3.106) <b>(d)</b> contrast material injection depict a precontrast decrease in size of the spiculated mass in <b>c</b> and no residual enhancement after contrast material injection in <b>d</b>. The findings from the final histopathologic examination disclosed a 2-mm residual focus of DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig10b.jpeg" height="651" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> ER-positive PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 43-year-old woman treated with neoadjuvant chemotherapy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR images (10/4.2) obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> contrast material injection show an enhancing irregular spiculated mass in <b>b</b>; the signal void corresponds to the metallic postbiopsy marker. <b>(c, d)</b> After the completion of neoadjuvant chemotherapy, axial T1-weighted MR images obtained before (8.159/4.603) <b>(c)</b> and after (6.289/3.106) <b>(d)</b> contrast material injection depict a precontrast decrease in size of the spiculated mass in <b>c</b> and no residual enhancement after contrast material injection in <b>d</b>. The findings from the final histopathologic examination disclosed a 2-mm residual focus of DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig10c.jpeg" height="639" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> ER-positive PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 43-year-old woman treated with neoadjuvant chemotherapy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR images (10/4.2) obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> contrast material injection show an enhancing irregular spiculated mass in <b>b</b>; the signal void corresponds to the metallic postbiopsy marker. <b>(c, d)</b> After the completion of neoadjuvant chemotherapy, axial T1-weighted MR images obtained before (8.159/4.603) <b>(c)</b> and after (6.289/3.106) <b>(d)</b> contrast material injection depict a precontrast decrease in size of the spiculated mass in <b>c</b> and no residual enhancement after contrast material injection in <b>d</b>. The findings from the final histopathologic examination disclosed a 2-mm residual focus of DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130049/asset/images/large/rg.345130049.fig10d.jpeg" height="640" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> ER-positive PR-negative HER2-positive infiltrating ductal carcinoma in a 43-year-old woman treated with neoadjuvant chemotherapy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR images (10/4.2) obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> contrast material injection show an enhancing irregular spiculated mass in <b>b</b>; the signal void corresponds to the metallic postbiopsy marker. <b>(c, d)</b> After the completion of neoadjuvant chemotherapy, axial T1-weighted MR images obtained before (8.159/4.603) <b>(c)</b> and after (6.289/3.106) <b>(d)</b> contrast material injection depict a precontrast decrease in size of the spiculated mass in <b>c</b> and no residual enhancement after contrast material injection in <b>d</b>. The findings from the final histopathologic examination disclosed a 2-mm residual focus of DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130049&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">American Cancer